    },
    {
      "id": "5e1e27bcfafd297a6208814395efd800a3b030cf",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 377,
        "name": "wc-checkpatch",
        "username": "hpdd-checkpatch",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2018-03-08 18:09:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nThis change cannot be cherry-picked to master.\nPlease rebase the change locally and upload the rebased commit for review.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3c53543231172d775f24abbd12104c4edd90b6d0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-03-09 01:37:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Benchmark:\n > 8 byte append w/dd:\n > dd if=/dev/zero bs=8 oflag=append of=./testfile\n\nWhat is the file size here?  I tested with count=1000000 to good effect.\n\n > 3.6 MB/s w/patch\n > ~720 KB/s w/out patch\n > \n > So about a 4x improvement for Lustre, in a pretty narrow case.\n\nIt would be great to include such information in the commit comment.\n\nMy local VM testing of this 8-byte append workload showed ~3.7MB/s to Lustre w/o the patch (tmpfs OSTs), and 6.7MB/s directly to tmpfs.  Running on real hardware (1GigE + HDD OSTs, i5-6600@3.30GHz CPU) it was 1.9 MB/s for Lustre and 21.7MB/s tmpfs, so a bit more of a difference but this is still slow no matter how you slice it.\n\nThis makes me wonder if tiny appends is the right thing to be optimizing?  Running with bs=4096 count=100000 appends shows a much larger difference between Lustre and tmpfs (6x in my VM, and 110MB/s vs. 3.0GB/s = 27x on my test node) so there are definitely larger improvements to be had for large appends vs. tiny ones.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7d6fe60298687dd2fae38bfd7f41039c32af5fde",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-03-09 03:43:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nSure, I'll put that info in the commit message if/when I clean this up to get it ready for possible landing.\n\nAbout 4K i/o: Certainly there are larger improvements to be had, but 4K append performs not that differently from normal 4K I/O in my testing, and I haven't come up with any great *simple* ideas for improving write performance for writes of 1 page or greater.\n\nTiny writes specifically depends on having a dirty page to skip the complex work of prepping a page for i/o on Lustre.  The only way I can think of to do the same at 4K and up is some version of Jinshan's containers idea.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "31b5b51b36472c9e9aef8bc102f3b2b555865919",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-03-09 03:51:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAh, and you asked what the file size was...  I tested until I got consistent results, which happened after a few seconds of i/o.  Files were a few 10s of MiB in size.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
